enues and unconditional transfers of these revenues to provinces based on fiscal need. Robert Wardhaugh and Barry Ferguson dig through the evidence and counter misconceptions to demonstrate that even though the report was at first rejected, it provided a storehouse of innovative ideas that redefined the nature of federal government and shaped policy – and thinking – about federalism for decades.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFederal governmentzCanadaxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aFederal governmentzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIntergovernmental fiscal relationszCanadaxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aIntergovernmental fiscal relationszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBothwell, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnglish, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerguson, Barry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311141764640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486503640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774865036423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774865036/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-141764-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles